 **Never** ignore an escalation or force the same model to retry without changes. If the implementer said it's stuck, something needs to change.

+## Review Loop Limits
+
+- **Max iterations:** 10 for any review loop (spec compliance or code quality). After 10 iterations with unresolved critical or important issues, escalate to the user.
+- **Minor issues don't block:** Note them in the task completion report but proceed to the next task. Do not loop on minor-only feedback.
+- **Same-issue cap:** If the same issue appears in 3 consecutive review cycles, escalate — the implementer and reviewer disagree on how to fix it.
+
+## Comment Cleanup Pass
+
+After code quality review approves (or only minor issues remain), run a quick cleanup before marking the task complete:
+
+- Strip comments that restate what the code does (`// Initialize the logger`, `// Return the result`)
+- Strip AI-obvious comments (apply `humanizer` patterns — no "Ensures proper...", "Leverages...", "Facilitates...")
+- Humanize remaining comments, docstrings, and error messages — direct and specific, no filler
+- Keep only comments that explain *why* something is done a non-obvious way
+
+This is a quick pass, not a full rewrite — if comments are already clean, skip it.
+
+## Pre-Merge User Review
+
+After the final code reviewer approves and before invoking `finishing-a-development-branch`, give the user a ready-to-run diff command so they can review all changes from their own terminal:
+
+```
+To review the full diff before we proceed:
+
+  git diff main...<worktree-branch>
+```
+
+Replace `<worktree-branch>` with the actual branch name. Three-dot (`main...<branch>`) shows only the changes introduced on the branch, even if main has advanced. Use branch-based diff, not path-based (`git -C <worktree-path> diff`).
+
+Wait for the user to confirm before continuing to the finishing skill. If the user requests changes, address them and re-present the diff command.
+
